### 2. YANG-Push to Message Broker Integration
* **Presenters:** Thomas Graf and Ahmed Bouguerra
* **Slides:** 
  * [YANG-Push to Message Broker Integration Status Update and Hackathon](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-nmop-sessa-2-yang-push-to-message-broker-integration-status-update-and-hackathon-01)
  * [YANG Message Keys for Message Broker Integration](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-nmop-yang-message-keys-for-message-broker-integration-00)
* **Drafts:** 
  * `draft-ietf-nmop-yang-message-broker-integration`
  * `draft-ietf-nmop-message-broker-telemetry-message`
  * `draft-ietf-nmop-yang-message-broker-message-key`
* **Discussion:**
  * Thomas reported that revisions 12 and 13 of `draft-ietf-nmop-yang-message-broker-integration` added security/operational considerations and detailed how schema deviations are handled by consumers and producers. Thomas suggested that `draft-ietf-nmop-yang-message-broker-integration` and `draft-ietf-nmop-message-broker-telemetry-message` are ready for WGLC, while `draft-ietf-nmop-yang-message-broker-message-key` should follow later once its proof of concept is more stable.
  * Thomas summarized Hackathon achievements, including testing additional YANG-push features (TLS, CBOR name identifiers, and IETF subscriptions) and completing integration tests with Ciena Blue Planet and Six Wind.
  * Ahmed presented updates on `draft-ietf-nmop-yang-message-broker-message-key`. The draft introduces a deterministic, three-phase algorithm to extract keys from subscriptions (XPath normalization, key template derivation, and key-value extraction) to prevent head-of-line blocking on message brokers.
  * A CLI implementation of this key extraction algorithm has been written in Rust and is available on GitHub.
  * Rob Wilton noted that YANG prefixes are not guaranteed to be unique across multiple vendors or devices. Ahmed replied that the algorithm falls back to hashing the final path element if collisions occur. Rob suggested that checking prefixes against a device schema registry and dynamically allocating unique alternatives could resolve this. Thomas noted that while names are unique per device, they are hard to guarantee across a multi-vendor network, making the namespace the only truly unique key. However, namespaces are too long for practical broker topic names.

