### 3. YANG Data Model for Network Incident Management
* **Presenter:** Chen Li
* **Slides:** [YANG Data Model for Network Incident Management](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-nmop-yang-data-model-for-network-incident-management-01)
* **Draft:** `draft-ietf-nmop-network-incident-yang`
* **Discussion:**
  * Recent updates resolved alignment issues with the terminology draft, corrected model references, made the "incident number" field mandatory, and added an operational considerations section.
  * The model now adopts a bottom-up approach to align with the RFC 8969 three-layer architecture (service, network, device) to easily map incidents to network anomaly architecture components.
  * Reshad Rahman asked why the 64-bit "incident number" is not used as the primary key for the YANG list, instead of the three-tuple (name, type, incident ID). Chen Li explained that they coexist so that IPC and notifications can use a single attribute (incident number) to identify incidents quickly and improve parsing performance. Reshad noted he would review the author's response in detail to understand why both are necessary.
  * Benoit Claise (document shepherd) stated he needs to perform a final review of the interaction between this model and the network anomaly detection drafts to ensure the mapping layer is fully aligned.

