### 5. CMOP/SIMAP YANG Modeling Direction
* **Presenters:** Olga Havel, Italo Busi, and Reshad Rahman
* **Slides:**
  * [SIMAP Modelling based on RFC8345 with some extensions](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-nmop-simap-modelling-based-on-rfc8345-with-some-extensions-00)
  * [Applicability of RFC8795 YANG data model to SIMAP](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-nmop-sessa-7-applicability-of-rfc8795-yang-data-model-to-simap-00)
  * [SIMAP YANG discussions and decision](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-nmop-sessa-8-simap-yang-discussions-and-decision-02)
* **Discussion:**
  * The working group has been split between two modeling paths: basing CMOP/SIMAP on the generic RFC 8345 topology model or on the traffic-engineered (TE) RFC 8795 topology model.
  * **RFC 8345 Approach (Olga Havel):** Olga argued that RFC 8345 is fully technology-agnostic and relies on simple "network, node, TP, link, and supporting" structures. It has been successfully implemented in multiple multi-technology hackathons. Olga favored "Option 4," which uses both models depending on the use case. RFC 8345 would serve as a generic, top-down navigation layer (for L2/L3, VPNs, and non-TE layers), while RFC 8795 would remain the authoritative model for active TE/optical control and configuration. Dan and Nigel Davis supported Option 4 as a pragmatic operational solution.
  * **RFC 8795 Approach (Italo Busi):** Italo argued against application-specific models, warning they lead to data duplication and integration challenges for operators. He advocated using RFC 8795 as a single base model and employing "profiles" (pruning unused leaves using deviations or subsets) to tailor the schema to specific applications. Rob Wilton cautioned that deviations are structurally intended to represent a device's non-conformance to a standard, rather than to define brand-new specifications.
  * Thomas Graf voiced concern that if Option 3 (RFC 8795 only with heavy profiling) is selected, anomaly detection systems might struggle to refer to a stable, predictable YANG schema tree.
  * Reshad Rahman summarized the choices and initiated a poll on Option 4 (using both approaches with use-case-specific scopes and accepting some navigational overlap).

